dmail function is invoked with correct parameters, but would never catch SMTP-level failures. An Integration test could verify that the report is formatted correctly and the send function is called, but would not catch delivery failures. A System test with a real SMTP server (or test SMTP service like Mailhog) verifies that the email is actually sendable and reachable. The REAL-INFRA question: does behavior depend on real network? Yes — the whole point is inbox delivery.","test_description":"Configure a test SMTP service (e.g., Mailhog, or a cloud email testing service). Run the complete pipeline: collect data from test doubles of the three sources, generate the summary (real LLM or deterministic mock), format the report, and send the email to a configured test recipient address. Verify that: (1) the email arrives in the test inbox, (2) the recipient address matches the configured value, (3) the subject line and body contain expected report content (summary, key metrics), and (4) headers are correct (From, Date, etc.).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"System level is required because real SMTP interaction and inbox delivery are the core failure boundary.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior requires verifying that: (1) when SMTP fails, the report is persisted to disk, and (2) on the next run, the script finds and retries delivery of the saved report. Real failures include: error handling for SMTP failures is missing, file save is not called or fails silently, backup file format is wrong, and the next run doesn't detect or clean up old files. A Unit test with mocked file operations could verify that the logic flow is correct (if SMTP fails, call save), but would not catch actual file I/O errors or state-persistence issues. An Integration test with real file I/O, two script invocations, and a mocked SMTP failure catches this: it verifies that the file is actually created, contains valid data, and is found and processed on the next run. System-level testing of real SMTP unavailability is not necessary — mocking SMTP failure at Integration level is sufficient.","test_description":"Configure SMTP to fail with a connection refused error (mocked). Run the report script, and verify that: (1) a backup report file is created in the configured directory with the expected content and naming (e.g., 'report_backup_2026-03-28.json'), (2) the script exits cleanly without raising an exception. Then restore SMTP (mocked to succeed), run the script again, and verify that: (3) the script detects the backup file, (4) the report is re-sent via email, (5) the backup file is deleted after successful delivery, (6) the email in the test inbox has the same report content as the original.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration level test with real file I/O and two invocations directly exercises the persistence and retry behavior without requiring real SMTP or OS-level scheduling.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13374,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13374},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ce2b7c97-a5a0-4062-bc6c-8dccaae85f92","uuid":"2b6a1578-de4d-4d88-94aa-fc8a049c943a"}
